# Parser error recovery — skip-to-sync-token (`recoverUntil`)

Demonstrates `PRecoverUntil`: when the inner parser fails, the runner
advances to the next occurrence of the sync token and continues parsing.

```scalascript
[Position, ParseError, ParseOk, ParseErr, Parser,
 PChar, PString, PRegex, PSatisfy, PSucceed, PFail](std/parsing/core.ssc)
[PSequence, PChoice, PMany, POpt, PMapped, PFlatMapped, PNamed,
 runParser](std/parsing/combinators.ssc)
[PRecoverUntil, PErrorNode, PParseAll, ErrorNode, ParseErrors,
 runParserAll, advanceToSync](std/parsing/recovery.ssc)

// A parser that expects the keyword "val".
val pVal: Parser[String] = Parser.string("val")

// On failure, skip to next semicolon and return the sentinel "<error>".
val pValRecover: Parser[Any] = pVal.recoverUntil(Parser.string(";"), "<error>")

// Input 1: well-formed — parser succeeds, no recovery needed.
val ok1 = runParserAll(PRecoverUntil(pVal, Parser.string(";"), "<error>"), "val", Position(0), Nil)
ok1 match
  case (Some(ParseOk(v, _, _)), errs) =>
    println("ok:" + v)
    println("errors:" + errs.length)
  case _ => println("unexpected")

// Input 2: bad keyword, semicolon at position 3.
// Runner skips "foo" and consumes ";", then returns default "<error>".
val ok2 = runParserAll(PRecoverUntil(pVal, Parser.string(";"), "<error>"), "foo;rest", Position(0), Nil)
ok2 match
  case (Some(ParseOk(v, rest, _)), errs) =>
    println("recovered:" + v)
    println("remaining:" + rest)
    println("errors:" + errs.length)
  case _ => println("unexpected")

// Input 3: bad keyword, no semicolon — exhausts input, returns default at end.
val ok3 = runParserAll(PRecoverUntil(pVal, Parser.string(";"), "<error>"), "garbage", Position(0), Nil)
ok3 match
  case (Some(ParseOk(v, rest, _)), errs) =>
    println("exhausted:" + v)
    println("remaining-empty:" + (rest == ""))
    println("errors:" + errs.length)
  case _ => println("unexpected")
```
